Interesting approach! 

> 11220 (44*255) bytes for the sig buffer,

We need to sign RTCM messages, not SBP messages, so I think this would actually be 44KB (44*1024).

I also wonder if it is worth building this level of complexity into the protocol? I think a client could implement a similar scheme themselves, if they wanted to, by having a similar fixed-size hashmap (which, if I'm understanding correctly, is essentially what we'd be building server side in your proposal)? In this case, they'd implement something like (excuse the very rough sketch):

```
void on_msg(uint32_t crc, void* buf) {
     fixed_hashmap->insert(crc, buf);
}

bool on_signature(uint32_t* crcs, uint32_t* sig) {
     uint8_t buf[max_size];
     for (crc in crcs) {
       buf.insert(fixed_hashmap->get(crc));
     }

     return verify_sig(sig, buf);
}
```

And in this way, it doesn't preclude clients that are happy to use dynamic memory from implementing the verification in a simpler fashion, if they chose to (by using a standard hashmap).

And not to reroute to start talking about message ordering again, but if we need to account for to non-guaranteed message ordering then I think a client could still need to buffer messages from other groups if the full group hasn't arrived yet. I guess in practice, if a client needed to use fixed buffers, you'd have to start dropping the oldest (by arrival time?) messages once you've buffered as much as possible.

