Technically, this is a binary breaking change. Though, I don't know if it'd affect anyone in practice since folks generally compile the source program each time, and it's unlikely anyone is passing a `cancellationToken` or overriding `InstallPluginAsync`.

If we did want to make it a binary compatible change, we'd need to add another overload. I can imagine two different approaches.

## Approach 1

Keep the existing method as-is, but change `abstract` to `virtual` and add a new `virtual` overload with the new parameter that throws:

```c#
public abstract class Workspace : IDisposable
{
    // Existing method changed from `abstract` to `virtual` and calls the new overload.
    public virtual Task InstallPluginAsync(string name, string version, PluginKind kind = PluginKind.Resource, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
        => InstallPluginAsync(name, version, kind, null, cancellationToken);

    // New virtual overload, that just throws at runtime.
    public virtual Task InstallPluginAsync(string name, string version, PluginKind kind = PluginKind.Resource, PluginInstallOptions? options = null, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
        => throw new NotSupportedException($"{nameof(InstallPluginAsync)} must be overridden");
}

public sealed class LocalWorkspace : Workspace
{
    public override Task InstallPluginAsync(string name, string version, PluginKind kind = PluginKind.Resource, PluginInstallOptions? options = null, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        // ... current implementation in PR ...
    }
}
```

The upside of this approach is is only requires subclasses to override a single virtual method. The downside is that these are no longer abstract, so there's no way to force a subclass to implement it, aside from the runtime exception. Most of this is a moot point because in practice only our own `LocalWorkspace` will be subclassing it.

## Approach 2

Keep the existing methods as-is (remains `abstract`) and add a new virtual overload with the new option that calls the existing abstract overload, ignoring the passed-in `PluginInstallOptions`. It'd be up to a subclass to override either the existing abstract overload alone to support the current functionality, or both to be able to support the new `PluginInstallOptions`.

```c#
public abstract class Workspace : IDisposable
{
    // Existing abstract method with no changes.
    public abstract Task InstallPluginAsync(string name, string version, PluginKind kind = PluginKind.Resource, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default);

    // New virtual method that can be overridden to support the new options.
    public virtual Task InstallPluginAsync(string name, string version, PluginKind kind = PluginKind.Resource, PluginInstallOptions? options = null, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        // By default, call the existing abstract `InstallPluginAsync` overload, which ignores `PluginInstallOptions`.
        // A subclass can override both to add support for `PluginInstallOptions`.
        return InstallPluginAsync(name, version, kind, cancellationToken);
    }
}

public sealed class LocalWorkspace : Workspace
{
    public override Task InstallPluginAsync(string name, string version, PluginKind kind = PluginKind.Resource, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
        => InstallPluginAsync(name, version, kind, null, cancellationToken);

    public override Task InstallPluginAsync(string name, string version, PluginKind kind = PluginKind.Resource, PluginInstallOptions? options = null, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        // ... current implementation in PR ...
    }
}
```

If we do want to make a binary compatible change, is there a preference on which approach we'd want to take?

